Part I - (Pima Indians Diabetes Dataset)¶

by Chukwunonso E. Chukwumaeze¶

Introduction¶

This dataset is originally from the National Institute of Diabetes and Digestive and Kidney Diseases, version was downloaded from Kaggle

The datasets consists of several medical predictor variables and one target variable, Outcome. Predictor variables includes the number of pregnancies the patient has had, their BMI, insulin level, age, and so on

Several constraints were placed on the selection of these instances from a larger database. In particular, all patients here are females at least 21 years old of Pima Indian heritage.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset contains about 768 rows with 9 columns. For my analysis I would be working on all rows and columns which includes:

  • pregnancies : Number of times pregnant
  • glucose : Plasma glucose concentration in a 2 hour oral glucose tolerance test. (mg/dL) Read More about this test here
  • blood_pressure : Diastolic blood pressure (mmHg)
  • skin_thickness : Triceps skin fold thickness (mm)
  • insulin : 2-Hour serum insulin(mu U/ml)Read More about Insulin Tests here
  • bmi : Body Mass Index (weight in kg/(height in m)^2)
  • diabetes_pedigree_function : indicates the function which scores likelihood of diabetes based on family history.
  • age : everyone in this dataset is above 21 years old.
  • diabetes : whether individuals have diabetes or not, 0 - No, 1- Yes.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I'm interested in the features that would be best predictors for diabetes in an individual

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

All these features play a huge role as indicators for diabetes but I think these ones would have a stronger effect:

  • glucose
  • insulin
  • bmi
  • blood_pressure
  • diabetes

3. BMI Category¶

BMI as a Diagnosing Tool for Body Fatness.¶

  • BMI are grouped into categories to vaguely define a person body fatness and what health risks they might be at risk for.

  • As such I would be categorising the BMI of the individuals into groups for a better idea of their body fatness.

  • A new column using the CDC Guidelines would be used to classify the BMI column into ordered categories.

In [20]:
#  Using pd.cut to group the bmi into categories

bins = [-np.inf, 18.4, 24, 29, 34, 39, np.inf ]
labels = ['underweight','healthy-weight','overwieight','class-1-obesity','class-2-obesity','class-3-obesity']
df['bmi_category'] = pd.cut(df.bmi, bins=bins, labels=labels)

Having a lot of zero values which is not possible after a 2-hour serum-insulin test.

In [32]:
zero_values = (df[df.insulin==0]['insulin']).count()

print(f'{zero_values}, \nPercentage composition of zero values: {((zero_values/df.shape[0])*100)}')

374, 
Percentage composition of zero values: 48.69791666666667

About 48% of the data is zero, the zero values will be replaced using the ffil() forward fill method Here's why:

  • Replacing with mean or median would automatically create a mode of the value, since we would be replacing 48% of the whole column.
  • Using the ffil method uses different values in respect to the position of the zero value and is appropriate since they're scattered all over the column, attributing a measure of randomness to the method.
In [33]:
# Replacing the zero values with null so as to use the ffill() function
df.insulin.replace(0, np.nan, inplace=True)

df.insulin.fillna(method='ffill', inplace=True)

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Age of Diabetic participants were significantly higher than non-diabetic participants
  • Age of diabetic patients reduced with increase in their BMI category
  • Underweight individuals had no diabetic participant and were very much younger than other BMI categories
  • Glucose and Insulin levels had a positive correlation in both diabetic and non-diabetic participants
  • Glucose levels had the highest positive correlation with diabetes outcome, with a Pearson's Correlation Coefficient of 0.49

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Blood Pressure distribution did not vary much among diabetic and non-diabetic participants.

Conclusions¶

The older the participants were, the more susceptible they became to having diabetes, with the age distribution of diabetic participants having clusters around the 30 and 40 year mark.

Glucose levels has the highest correlation with the diabetic status of the participant.
